title: A Phase Ib/IIa Multicenter, Double-Blind, Randomized, Placebo-Controlled Study to Evaluate the Safety, Tolerability and Immunogenicity of Different Doses, Regimens and Combinations of Tau Targeted Vaccines in Subjects With Early Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This study is a multicenter, double blind, randomized, placebo-controlled study to evaluate the safety, tolerability and immunogenicity of different doses, regimens and combinations of Tau targeted vaccines in participants with early Alzheimer's Disease.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails:
Screening details:

Subjects between 50 and 75 years at screening with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) due to AD or Mild AD according to NIA-AA criteria, providing a written informed consent and fulfilling all further inclusion criteria could enter the clinical trial.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: Recruitment was performed in Finland, the Netherlands, Sweden and the UK. 79 subjects were screened for the study; 22 subjects did not meet the eligibility criteria; 1 subject was re-screened and qualified to participate.

measures.title: Clinical Dementia Rating (CDR) - Global Score
measures.description: The CDR Scale is used to assess the function of AD subjects in six categories: memory, orientation, judgement and problem solving, community affairs, home and hobbies and personal care. It is based on an interview of the subject and caregiver. Each category is scored from 0 (no symptoms) to 3 (severe). The CDR global score is derived from scores of each individual category (obtained after computation with an algorithm) and ranges from 0 to 3 (severity of symptoms: 0=normal, 0.5 = very mild, 1=mild, 2=moderate, 3=severe). This score was an inclusion criteria (score of 0.5 or 1 at Screening).

measures.title: Concomitant Medication
measures.description: Number of subjects under Acetylcholinesterase Inhibitors and/or Memantine medication at baseline (prior to first dosing).

measures.title: Mini Mental State Examination (MMSE) Total score
measures.description: The Mini Mental State Examination (MMSE) is a widely used test of overall cognitive function, assessing memory, orientation and praxis in a short series of tests and questions. The total score (sum of score for each test question) ranges from 0 to 30 with 30 being the best possible score and 0 being the worst possible score. This score was part of the inclusion criteria (score of 22 or above at Screening).

outcomeMeasures.title: Overview of Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events, Safety Set
outcomeMeasures.description: Categorical data are presented with the number of subjects with at least one event for the defined categories. Subjects are included only once, even if they experienced multiple events in a category.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Observations are given for the Safety population (all randomized subjects who received at least one dose of the study drug, analyzed based on the study treatment actually received). All 57 subjects randomized in the study received at least 1 dose of the study drug according to their randomized treatment and are therefore all included in the Safety population, which is identical to the Intention-to Treat (ITT) population (all randomized subjects who received at least one dose of the study drug).
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: AEs falling between first dosing (week 0) and last study visit (week 74), ie up to 74 weeks, defined as Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events (TEAEs)

outcomeMeasures.title: Overview of Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events Assessed by Intensity, Safety Set
outcomeMeasures.description:
Categorical data are presented with the number of subjects with at least one Treatment-Emergent Adverse Event (TEAE) assessed as:

* Mild: Easily tolerated and causes minimal discomfort and does not interfere with everyday activities.
* Moderate: Sufficiently discomforting to interfere with normal everyday activities; intervention may be needed. Event is not hazardous to the subject's health
* Severe: Prevents normal everyday activities; treatment or other intervention usually needed. Hazard to the subject's health

Although subjects may have experienced multiple events, they are included only once, in the maximum severity category
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Observations are given for the Safety population (all randomized subjects who received at least one dose of the study drug, analyzed based on the study treatment actually received). All 57 subjects randomized in the study received at least 1 dose of the study drug according to their randomized treatment and are therefore all included.

outcomeMeasures.title: Overview of Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events Assessed by Relationship to Study Drug, Safety Set
outcomeMeasures.description:
Categorical data are presented with the number of subjects with at least one Treatment-Emergent Adverse Event (TEAE) assessed as:

* Unrelated: Events reported as unrelated or unlikely related to study drug
* Related: Events reported as possibly related or probably related to study drug

Although subjects may have experienced multiple events, they are included only once, in the strongest relationship category

outcomeMeasures.title: Mean Change From Baseline in Diastolic Blood Pressure, ITT Set
outcomeMeasures.description:
At reported visits, diastolic blood pressures (mmHg = millimeter of mercury) were measured in sitting position only, after the subject has been sitting down for at least 5 minutes.

A change from baseline value is defined as the value at post-baseline timepoint minus the baseline value, i.e. post-baseline value - baseline value
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: ITT population (i.e. all randomized subjects who received at least 1 dose of the study drug).
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Endpoint is assessed from baseline (i.e. last non-missing value prior to the first immunization at week 0) to the last study visit (week 74), at weeks 26, 50 and 74.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline of Functional Performance Using CDR-SB Scale
outcomeMeasures.description: CDR-SB means Clinical Dementia Rating - Sum of Boxes. The score ranges from 0 to 18. A higher score indicates a worse outcome.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline of Cognitive Performance Using RBANS Scale
outcomeMeasures.description: RBANS means Repeatable Battery for the Assessment of Neuropsychological Status. The total scale index score ranges from 40 to 160. A higher score indicates a better outcome.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline of Behavior Using NPI Scale
outcomeMeasures.description: NPI means Neuropsychiatric Inventory. The score ranges from 0 to 144. A higher score indicates a worse outcome.

adverseEventsModule.timeFrame: The safety reporting period covering any Adverse Events which were treatment-emergent is the interval between the first dosing (Visit 1, Week 0) and the last safety follow-up visit (Visit 11, Week 74); up to 74 weeks.
adverseEventsModule.description:
Determination of Adverse Events was based on:

* the signs or symptoms detected during the physical examination of the subject and on clinical assessments (e.g. laboratory values, MRI results etc.)
* the interview of the subject and their caregiver

limitationsAndCaveats.description:
* The study was not powered to detect differences between the active and placebo treatments for exploratory endpoints (e.g., fluid biomarkers and cognition/clinical efficacy outcomes).
* The sub-cohort 1.1 (ACI-35.030 300 μg / placebo) was significantly impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic due to local travel restriction in Finland. Seven out of 8 subjects (5 active and 2 placebo) in this sub-cohort missed 1 study treatment administration.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: Publication shall not be made by PIs before a first multi-site publication by Sponsor. If no multi-site publication is made within 18 months after study completion, PIs can publish under conditions: Prior any publication submission, PI shall send Sponsor any information to be disclosed and Sponsor have 60 days from receipt to review and comment. PI shall remove any Confidential Information and upon Sponsor request further delay publication for up to 120 days to protect Sponsor interests.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests active vaccines designed to elicit antibodies against pathological Tau (phosphorylated/aggregated tau) in early Alzheimer’s disease, which is a biologic, disease-targeted intervention rather than a small molecule, symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or neuropsychiatric treatment. citeturn0search1turn1search3

Act: The study title and sponsor identify the investigational agents as two tau-targeted vaccines, ACI-35.030 and JACI-35.054, administered versus placebo in a randomized, double-blind Phase Ib/IIa design to evaluate safety, tolerability and immunogenicity. citeturn0search1turn1search0

Supporting evidence: AC Immune’s press releases and clinical summaries describe ACI-35.030 as a liposomal active immunotherapy (vaccine) designed to generate antibodies selective for phosphorylated/aggregated Tau (pTau/ePHF) and report strong immunogenicity and favorable safety signals in the Phase 1b/2a trial. JACI-35.054 is the other vaccine evaluated in the same study. citeturn1search3turn1search4

Reflect: Classification check — vaccines are biologics that target Alzheimer’s pathology (tau) with the intent of modifying disease (reducing pathological tau and its spread). This fits the definition of 'disease-targeted biologic' and not the other categories (small molecule, cognitive enhancer, or neuropsychiatric symptom improvement). No alternative interpretation fits the description. citeturn0search1turn1search5
explanation_agent: Reason: The trial tests active (liposomal) vaccines designed to elicit antibodies against pathological, phosphorylated/aggregated Tau (pTau/ePHF), i.e., the intervention directly targets Tau pathology rather than neurotransmission or symptomatic processes. citeturn0search4turn0search2

Act: The investigational agents named (ACI-35.030 and JACI-35.054) are AC Immune’s anti-pTau active immunotherapies (liposomal vaccines) shown in Phase 1b/2a to induce anti-pTau antibodies and favorable safety/tolerability; ACI-35.030 has been advanced for further development. citeturn0search6turn0search5turn0search1

Supporting web evidence (key search results found): peer-reviewed Phase 1b/2a results and company releases describing ACI-35.030 and JACI-35.054 as vaccines targeting phosphorylated/aggregated Tau and reporting immunogenicity and safety. citeturn0search0turn0search3

Reflect: This is a disease-targeted biologic whose mechanism is anti-Tau immunization (disease-modifying intent), which maps directly to CADRO category B (Tau). No evidence in the description points to multiple distinct biological targets, non-therapeutic imaging, or other CADRO categories, so 'B) Tau' is the most specific fit. citeturn0search4turn0search6
